BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 333.70 Tm (JSON - JavaScript Object Notation - is the format your API will send and receive, so let's make it) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 318.70 Tm (land. Look at the single student object. Curly braces wrap one object - one record. Inside are) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 303.70 Tm (key-value pairs: the key is always a quoted string, then a colon, then the value. Commas separate) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 288.70 Tm (the pairs. Values can be strings in quotes, bare numbers, or booleans - true and false. The second) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 273.70 Tm (example shows square brackets, which make an array - an ordered list. So a response with) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 258.70 Tm (several students is an array of objects. And here's the good news - you won't write this by hand.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 243.70 Tm (Spring Boot uses a library called Jackson to automatically convert your Java objects into JSON on) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 228.70 Tm (the way out, and JSON back into objects on the way in. That conversion is called serialization.) Tj ET
